<capabilities>
<p>The Gurzil's most distinctive feature is its Series VI targeting and tracking system, acquired from Clan Sea Fox at considerable expense. This advanced system offers three preconfigured firing solutions optimized for different range brackets. When a firing solution is selected, the Series VI triples telemetry data sampling for targets within that bracket, dramatically improving accuracy. However, this enhancement comes at a cost: targets outside the selected range bracket receive significantly reduced tracking priority, creating potential blind spots during rapidly evolving engagements.</p>

<p>The tank's primary armament consists of twin Type XV Culverin Streak LRM-15 launchers and Series 14a Medium Pulse Lasers mounted in the turret. The Streak systems provide reliable direct fire support with minimal ammunition waste, while the pulse lasers offer capability against battle armor and hardened targets. Complementing the turret weapons are two Type VIII Mech Mortar/8 systems in forward-facing hull mounts, allowing indirect fire support from concealed positions. Twelve and a half tons of Ferro-Lamellor armor provide substantial protection, though the Gorvachs 320 XL fusion engine represents a potential vulnerability if that armor is breached. The 64 km/h top speed allows the Gurzil to maintain pace with medium formations while repositioning between engagements.</p>
</capabilities>

<overview>
<p>The Gurzil entered service with Clan Jade Falcon in 3126 as the Clan's answer to the ubiquitous JES II missile carrier. Manufactured by Wakazashi Enterprises, this 80-ton tracked support tank was designed to combine direct missile fire support with indirect mortar bombardment capabilities. This dual-role philosophy aimed to provide Falcon commanders with a single platform capable of adapting to varied tactical situations. In practice, the Gurzil's reception has been decidedly mixed. Commanders who understand and exploit its unique capabilities praise its performance, but many warriors consider the design a poor compromise that excels at neither role. Critics frequently advocate for dedicated single-role alternatives such as the JES II or Carnivore Support Tank, viewing the Gurzil's versatility as a liability rather than an asset.</p>
</overview>

